caption: The food was exceptional, with reasonably large portions!! From right to left, top to bottom: * Carrot ginger soup and grilled kale * Theibou Jen (fish dish, national Senegalese dish) * Vegetarian stew * Carrot ginger soup and branzino grille. The fish was cooked and seasoned perfectly. It is a whole fish so keep in mind that there will be bones * Yassa Guninar. Juicy, well spiced chicken  10/10 would go back. Outdoor seating was also nice (was a really nice day), and the service was good.

Major staple of Crown Heights and one of our favorites. I live on the block, and would eat here once a week if I could afford it. Excellent.

DON’T GO HERE. My friend and I went there and they overcharged us. We were pretty tired and hungry so we weren’t paying attention to the receipt they asked me to sign. But, later on, when we did our calculations, they added almost an extra $10 (not including taxes) to our bill and didn’t even give us a customer copy of our receipt. Not only that, they had us carry our own cups, big bottle of water, and utensils to our own table. We ordered in the front and waited to receive our foods. I felt like i was at Smashburger. We asked for straws and never got them. My friend had to get up and get them herself. There was nothing spectacular about the experience as a whole. The food wasn’t horrible but it was underwhelming. The beef Fataya were great however everything else was mediocre. It was my first time trying Senegalese food and I had The Thiebou Jen, which is the traditional Senegalese dish and I was not impressed. The rice was okay and the fish was dry. The gravy had an overpowering sour taste. I’m still open to giving Senegalese food another chance but was disappointed in this restaurant honestly. I doubt this is a native Senegalese owned restaurant. Very disappointed!
Great food and a nice little boutique next door owned by the same couple...

Unfortunately, I was not impressed by my visit here; I was beyond dissatisfied! You have to go to a window to order your food—felt like I was at a hood spot or a fast food joint. The food was overpriced. Worst of all, I later realized that I was overcharged. They didn’t even give a customer copy of the receipt, very sneaky. I’m not sure if they went ahead and added the tip without my knowing, but somehow we were charged $88 for what was advertised as a $72 meal (two fish dishes, one drink and one appetizer). On top of that, the hostess wasn’t very welcoming and honestly seemed annoyed. We then had to carry our own cups, water bottle and utensils to our table. The table was sticky and hadn’t been cleaned off properly, which is a big red flag, especially with Corona. It was crowded but there only seemed to be one waiter. He was odd. He had what looked like multiple Q-tips sticking out of his face mask; I guess it was a fashion statement, I’m not sure. All I know is that Halloween was over a week ago. Furthermore, his pants were sagging which is not what I wanna see when I’m eating. I asked the waiter for straws which I never even got; I later walked up to the hostess and had to get them myself. My drink was tasty but weak. The salmon wasn’t nasty but was underwhelming. It was dry, not medium well at all and I was expecting a salmon steak but it was a salmon fillet. It had no seasoning. It came with a cold, sweet, tomato tasting sauce—not my preference at all. The black olive mashed potatoes were fine. The kale wasn’t as crispy as described but was edible. The beef fataya was pretty good, however, some pieces had over cooked fried dough that were hard. Though, it was still the best thing we ordered. The sauce that came with it was extremely overpowering—way too spicy, and this is coming from someone who likes spicy food. My friend said her snapper was dry and that her veggies were too mushy and soft. She said the sauce that the fish came with was nasty and sour, she wasn’t sure what it was. Also, there was a loud group of people just standing by the restaurant, they weren’t even waiting to be seated. I’m not sure if they were friends with the owner or something but it was very tacky and concerning during COVID. This was my first time trying Senegalese food, I heard it was good. I was disappointed in this place, but I am open to trying other places in the future. Overall, it was a lackluster experience at this restaurant and I would not recommend. It didn’t seem that authentic to me. This place was trash and I would never come back and will warn my friends and peers to avoid it.

This was my first experience with Senegalese food. It was really good. The restaurant was small, more on the intimate side. We had the hummus vert as the app and it was really tasty. The fish was seasoned well, a little over for her tastes but only slightly. I had the dibi senegal - well seasoned and flavorful, a little over but only slightly. For drinks I had the marche rue dix which was really good and she had the hibiscus juice which was solid. The chocolate lava cake was good too. Our server was pleasant.  Overall, recommended. We will be back.

On July 22nd, 2020, I had lunch at Cafe Rue Dix. This was my first meal out since COVID and was excited to try this Senegalese restaurant. Unfortunately, that excitement soon went away.  The food we received tasted nothing like the Senegalese food I had and loved in the past. We left all our food uneaten after a few bites. However,  things got much worse when I took a bite of my lamb dibi and found hair in my food. I was disgusted.  We waited and waited for our waiter to return and when that never happened we left. I felt sick to my stomach and couldn’t take it anymore. Unfortunately, this restaurant forces you to pay for your meal before you receive it, even for dine-in, so they already had my payment.  I immediately, after leaving, called the restaurant and spoke to the manager, who accused me of putting my own hair in the food and refused to refund the charge for our meal, even with photographic proof and a note on the receipt concerning the hair.  This was a horrible dining and customer service experience.

This cute little unsuspecting French Senegalese restaurant with its open air aesthetic and stylish dark wood finishes provide the perfect backdrop for your next Brunch, Lunch or Dinner. Hands down the best Croque Madame in the city; it’s melted to perfection and nestled in a delightful bed of greens. I never fail to clean the plate! They offer a variety of cocktails, coffees, teas and homemade beverage - all refreshing and delicious. Menu options include anything from fresh salads to burgers, sandwiches, small bites, etc. It’s also a great spot to bring visiting family or relatives. Lots of healthy options and just solid food with a great staff!

Really wanted to like this place. Lived the in the neighborhood for a while always passed by and it looked fun. Came in late on a Wednesday with a friend, large party just leaving, maybe bad timing. The staff were very friendly, atmosphere great, music lively. Ordered the tuna tartare, octopus salad, moules frites, grilled shrimp, bottle of Argentinian Malbec. The shrimp and octopus were mushy, with no bounce. The mussels were good, though the sauce a little sweet for our taste. Nice crunchy fries though. May go again and try the brunch.
